ish and Irish: most probably an altered form of Welsh   Meredith   (which is found as <b>Meriday</b> in 16th and 17th century English sources), or possibly of English   Mayhew  . Compare   Mallalieu  ."]},{"name":"Merideth","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Meredith  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Verch Meredith was born in 1185, in Ystrad, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ieuan ap Gwilym. She died in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1185–":"1185–Surnud","1155–1205":"1155–1205","1200–1229":"1200–1229","1205–1270":"1205–1270","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1205":"1205","after 1205":"pärast 1205","ABT    1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","1185":"1185","1270":"1270","1229":"1229","Ystrad, Glamorgan, Wales":"Ystrad, Glamorgan, Wales, Unit